@Node GETS "GrabURL.guide/Getting Started"

@{jcenter}@{u}@{b}Getting Started@{ub}@{uu}@{jleft}

In the 2 following section, you will find how to quickly install & configure GrabURL and how to use it.

You should then read other sections to learn about what else GrabURL can do and how to configure it.

    @{" Quick Installation " Link QUICKINSTALL}
    @{" Examples           " Link EXAMPLES}


@EndNode

@Node QUICKINSTALL "GrabURL.guide/Quick Installation"

@{jcenter}@{u}@{b}Quick Installation@{ub}@{uu}@{jleft}

@{u}@{b}What is what@{ub}@{uu}

1) GrabURL: An ARexx program using GrabHTTP, UrlManager & ScanHTML to live.  It can download files via HTTP, scan them, download files referenced by the last one, etc...

2) GrabHTTP: A 'C' program.  This is used by ARexx scripts to download files using the protocol "HTTP".

3) UrlManager: A 'C' program.  This keeps a list of URLs in memory.  Used by GrabURL to keep and work with the list of files it has to download (ie not to get the same file 2 times).

4) ScanHTML: A 'C' program.  This scans HTML files and make a list of all referenced files contained in it.  (Also needed by GrabURL).

@{u}@{b}Quick Installation@{ub}@{uu}

1) Check if you have "rexxdossupport.library".  To do this, go in a shell and type:

    version rexxdossupport.library

   It should tells you something like:

    rexxdossupport.library 3.4

    @{lindent 4}The number "3.4" is the version of the library.  It should be at least 2.0.  If you don't have that library (ie version told something like "object not found") or if the library is too old, you should get it from AmiNet of from my web page (http://www.jsp.umontreal.ca/~emonds/GrabURL.html) and install it.@{lindent 0}


2) Install GrabURL with the provided installer-script.  You should choose a directory contained in your path.  If you are using AmiTCP, AmiTCP:bin is supposed to be in your path.  If you don't know what is a "path", look in your AmigaDOS manuel for the dos command "path".

3) Use an ASCII editor (ie GoldED, CignusEd, etc..) to edit "GrabURL".  Search for "opts.SaveRoot".  The string enclosed between " is the directory where the files you will download are saved.  It @{b}must@{ub} exists.  The default is "Work:urls".  When your directory is choosen, just save the modified GrabURL and exit your editor.

4) GrabURL should be ready to work now and you should jump to @{"Examples" Link EXAMPLES}.

@EndNode

@Node EXAMPLES "GrabURL.guide/Examples"

@{jcenter}@{u}@{b}Examples@{ub}@{uu}@{jleft}

In the precedent section (@{"Quick Installation" Link QUICKINSTALL}), you should have set a directory where to save the incomming files.  Lets suppose you kept the default setting, "Work:urls/"...

@{b}1 - Getting a single file@{ub}

Suppose you want to download GrabURL.readme from Aminet.  You can type this:

    @{i}GrabURL http://www.aminet.org/pub/aminet/comm/www/GrabURL.readme @{ui}

This will open a @{"window" Link GrabHTTP.guide/PROGRESS 0} showing the status of the download.  The file will be saved under the name

    Work:urls/www.aminet.org/pub/aminet/comm/www/GrabURL.readme

Don't forget: majs and mins are not the same thing.  If you wrote "graburl.readme" instead of "GrabURL.readme", GrabURL will tell you the file does not exist.

@{b}2 - Getting a single file and save it in ram:@{ub}

If you write the following:

    @{i}GrabURL saveroot ram: nodirs http://www.aminet.org/pub/aminet/comm/www/GrabURL.readme @{ui}

then it will download the file again, but this time it will save it under the name "ram:GrabURL.readme".

-> @{b}NoDirs@{ub} means "Don't create any directory".  Ie the file should be saved as "Work:urls/GrabURL.readme".  (Abbreviation: "r")

-> @{b}SaveRoot ram:@{ub} means "Change the save-directory to @{b}ram:@{ub}".  It is the same as setting "opts.SaveRoot" in GrabURL itself as told in @{"Quick Installation" Link QUICKINSTALL}. (Abbrev: "sr")

@{b}3 - Getting a whole web directory@{ub}

Suppose now that you want to download everything in the fictive web site "http://www.fictif.com/moly/", you could write the following:

    @{i}GrabURL http://www.fictif.com/moly/ recursive @{ui}

@{b}recursive@{ub} on the command-line can be abbreviated by @{b}r@{ub}.  It tells GrabURL to scan @{b}all@{ub} HTML file it receives.

First it will download "http://www.fictif.com/moly/index.html".  Then it will scan it.  Then it will download all the files it found inside "index.html", then scan the new files if they are HTML, then download, ....

This is not extremely useful since it could contains a reference to "http://www.yahoo.com/", and I don't think your hard drive is big enough to download the whole world.

@{b}4 - Getting a web directory intelligently@{ub}

GrabURL supports many selective options.  The most useful is @{b}pattern@{ub}, which can be abbreviated to @{b}p@{ub}.  Example:

    @{i}GrabURL r p #?moly/#? http://www.fictif.com/moly/ @{ui}

This will do the same as in the previous example, except that when scanning HTML files, it will only add files containing "moly/" in their complete name.  This way, it should grab http://www.fictif.com/moly/ and all what's in that directory, nothing more.

You can use any AmigaDOS pattern.  You should read your AmigaDOS manuel about patterns if you are not already familiar with them.

If you want to download only jpegs and gifs contained in moly/index.html, you could use this instead:

    @{i}GrabURL r p #?.(gif|jp#eg) http://www.fictif.com/moly/ @{ui}

Here, the pattern means:  anything containg a period (".") followed by either "gif" or "jp#eg".  "jp#eg" is also a pattern:  "#e" means "insert 0 or more 'e' here".  Ie the pattern "jp#eg" can match "jpg", "jpeg", "jpeeg", "jpeeeg", etc..


@{b}5 - Downloading URLs contained in a file@{ub}

If you create an ascii file named "ram:stuff" containing two lines:

    http://www.aminet.org/pub/aminet/comm/www/GrabURL.readme
    http://www.aminet.org/pub/aminet/comm/www/GrabURL.lha

You can then write in a shell:

    @{i}GrabURL infile ram:stuff @{ui}

and GrabURL will do exactly the same thing as if you write:

    @{i}GrabURL http://www.aminet.org/pub/aminet/comm/www/GrabURL.readme http://www.aminet.org/pub/aminet/comm/www/GrabURL.lha @{ui}

You can use @{b}if@{ub} instead of @{b}InFile@{ub} on the command line.

@{b}6 - Download a file only if it has been modified@{ub}

If one week ago you downloaded the lastest version of GrabURL with this:

    @{i}GrabURL http://www.jsp.umontreal.ca/~emonds/GrabURL.lzx @{ui}

it saved the file under the name "Work:urls/www.jsp.umontreal.ca/_emonds/GrabURL.lzx".  Now you want to download it again, but only if it has been modified.  You can write this:

    @{i}GrabURL ifmodified http://www.jsp.umontreal.ca/~emonds/GrabURL.lzx @{ui}

or

    @{i}GrabURL im http://www.jsp.umontreal.ca/~emonds/GrabURL.lzx @{ui}

GrabURL will ask for GrabURL.lzx and tell the remote host the date of the file on your hard drive.  If the remote file is newer, the host will send it.  If your file is newer or has the same date, GrabURL will simply tell you "Not modified" and will not re-download it.

Important notes:  some WWW servers still dont support all HTML-1.0 features -- don't blame me if you encounter some sites not supporting this feature!  There are also servers which will always send .html files regardless of the date but returns "Not modified" for other types of files.

@{b}7 - Using a workfile@{ub}

Suppose you are the kind of people who download entire AmiNet trees (or tons of images from various web sites ;-).  The result can be tons and tons of megs.

GrabURL allows you to use a "workfile" where all URLs in memory are saved, along with their status (received, failed, queued, etc..).  It can then be reused later to continue the transfer where it was left.  The default setting of GrabURL is to save the work-file @{b}each@{ub} time a file is received.  You can change the internal setting to save it only when it is finished (but is less secure if your electricity company is more like a shutdown company ;^).

For example, you want to download all views on AmiNet (ie pix/views directory):

    @{i}GrabURL workfile Work:Views.wf r p #?.jpg http://www.aminet.org/pub/aminet/pix/views/ @{ui}

This command line will get you the pix/views/index.html file and will add to the list everything ending with ".jpg".

Each time something is received, all urls are saved in "work:views.wf".  @{b}It contains the list of urls, not the command line used!@{ub}  If you abort the transfer after the 4th picture, then reopen your computer 3 days later and write:

    @{i}GrabURL wf work:views.wf @{ui}

then GrabURL will simply continue where the transfer was left.  You should know that there is no way to continue to download a file where it was.  If you stop after 10767 bytes, then the file will have to be retransferred from byte 0.

You should be careful with this options:  If you begins a grab with a pattern, stop it and then continue it @{b}without@{ub} giving the pattern and the recurvise option again, then it will only download the files listed in the workfile, it will not scan them.

The same way, if you give "r" on the command-line without the original pattern then it will simply grab anything it can find in then html files.

@{b}What's next@{ub}

I think the most common options have been spoken of.  You should now have a look at the other sections of this document to know how to use the other options and how to configure GrabURL.

@EndNode

@Node AUTHENTICATION "GrabURL.guide/Authentication"

@{jcenter}@{b}@{u}Authentication@{uu}@{ub}

@{jleft}Authentication is used by some servers to restrict files to registered users.  (Ie paying websites, development sites, ...) GrabURL supports the "Basic" authentication which is the only HTTP 1.0 official scheme.

The implementation is simple:  when a server returns the error "401 Unauthorized", it also send what is called a "realm": a string associated with a specific web site (a site may have multiple realms).

Upon reception of such an error, GrabURL looks in its database and send the appropriate username and password.

If you are registered on some sites then you should tell GrabURL about your informations so you can download protected files.

In order to do this, you have to create a file somewhere on your harddrive and put the name in the "def.PasswordFile" field.  (See the @{"Setting the defaults" Link DEFAULTS} section)

In this file, lines beginning with ";" are comments.  There should be one realm/line following this format:

    realm:userid:password

All information is case-sensitive and spaces means something...  Don't add extra spaces!!

Here's an example file:

@{b};Mumblio Programming @{}
Mumblio Prg:serge:molybden @{}
;SpiderWeb @{}
Spider Corp:serge:771xD @{ub}

In this file, I'm registered on the realm "Mumblio Prg", with the name "serge" and the password "molybden". Being a registered user for the fictive web browser SpiderWeb, I can download new versions with the same user name and the password "771xD".

If you don't know the realm of one or more places, simply tell GrabURL to download a protected file: it will tell you what is the realm.

For example, if you want to know the realm used on http://www.fictif.net/private/, just execute this:

@{b}GrabURL http://www.fictif.net/private/ @{ub}

You should get something like this:

@{b}[   1] http://www.fictif.net/private/... [Auth] Unknown realm: "Fictif Mumbo" @{ub}

which tells you that the realm is "Fictif Mumbo".

@EndNode

@Node ARGUMENTS "GrabURL.guide/Arguments"

@{jcenter}@{b}Arguments@{ub}@{uu}

@{jleft}GrabURL can only be used from a Shell.

You can stop it by sending CTRL-C.  If a file is being transferred, you should stop @{"GrabHTTP" Link GrabHTTP.guide/main 0} with the close gadget (or wait until the transfer is over).

    @{b}Text arguments@{ub}
    @{" URL          " Link A_URL}    Url to download.
    @{" PATTERN      " Link A_PATTERN}    Pattern to select urls.
    @{" INFILE       " Link A_INFILE}    File containing an url list.
    @{" SAVEROOT     " Link A_SAVEROOT}    Directory where to put urls.
    @{" WORKFILE     " Link A_WORKFILE}    File containing all urls with their flags.

    @{b}Numeric arguments@{ub}
    @{" DELAY        " Link A_DELAY}    Delay to wait between each grab.
    @{" DEPTH        " Link A_DEPTH}    Recursion level.
    @{" MAXCOUNT     " Link A_MAXCOUNT}    Max. number of file to grab.
    @{" MAXTIME      " Link A_MAXTIME}    Max. time to grab.
    @{" MAXSIZE      " Link A_MAXSIZE}    Max. size a file can have.
    @{" MINSPACELEFT " Link A_MSL}    Min. space to leave on disk.

    @{b}Switches@{ub}
    @{" HELP         " Link A_HELP}    Display arguments.
    @{" HEADERSONLY  " Link A_HEADONLY}    Save the headers but not the files.
    @{" IFMODIFIED   " Link A_IFMODIFIED}    Grab the file if modified since last grab.
    @{" NOBG         " Link A_NOBG}    Don't grab background images.
    @{" NODIRS       " Link A_NODIRS}    Don't create directories - save in current dir.
    @{" NOHREF       " Link A_NOHREF}    Don't grab referenced files.
    @{" NOSRC        " Link A_NOSRC}    Don't grab src urls.
    @{" NOTEXISTS    " Link A_NOTEXISTS}    Grab only if file does not exists on disk.
    @{" QUERY        " Link A_QUERY}    Allow '?' in urls.
    @{" RECURSIVE    " Link A_RECURS}    Allow recursion.
    @{" RETRY        " Link A_RETRY}    Retry urls that failed.
    @{" SAVEHEADERS  " Link A_SAVEHEADS}    Save transfer headers to disk.

@EndNode

@Node A_URL "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/URL"

@{b}URL@{ub}  (URL/M)

This allows you to add url(s) directly from the command line. These URLs will be flagged as @{"Queued" Link FLAGS}. You can add multiple urls this way. Any url added on the command line will prevail over file-urls. (Ie an url flagged received in the @{"workfile" Link A_WORKFILE} will be flagged not received).

An url must begins with "HTTP://" since this is the only protocol supported for now.

See also:
    @{" InFile   " Link A_INFILE}
    @{" WorkFile " Link A_WORKFILE}

@EndNode

@Node A_MAXCOUNT "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/MaxCount"

@{b}MaxCount@{ub}  (MAXCOUNT=MC/N) (Abbrev: MC)

This is the maximal number of file to download.  You can use this switch with @{"WorkFile" Link A_WORKFILE} to download only a defined number of file per day.  Use 0 disable this option.  Default = 0.

See also:
    @{" MaxTime  " Link A_MAXTIME}
    @{" MaxBytes " Link A_MAXBYTES}

@EndNode

@Node A_MAXTIME "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/MaxTime"

@{b}MaxTime@{ub}  (MAXTIME=MT/N) (Abbrev: MT)

This is the maximal time in minutes to download.  You can use this switch with @{"WorkFile" Link A_WORKFILE} to download only a certain time / day.  Use 0 to disable this option.  Default = 0.

This is not exact.  For example, if you specify MaxTime=10 and you download this:

    Bozo.jpg    3 mins (Tot: 3 mins)
    Clown.jpg   6 mins (Tot: 9 mins)
    Nuage.png   2 mins (Tot: 11 mins)
    <it stops here>

See also:
    @{" MaxBytes " Link A_MAXBYTES}
    @{" MaxCount " Link A_MAXCOUNT}

@EndNode

@Node A_MAXBYTES "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/MaxBytes"

@{b}MaxBytes@{ub}  (MAXBYTES=MB/N) (Abbrev: MB)

This is the maximal number of bytes to download.  You can use this switch with @{"WorkFile" Link A_WORKFILE} to download only a certain quantity of bytes per day.  Use 0 to disable this option.  Default = 0.

This is not an exact number.  For example, if you specify MaxBytes=4096 and you download this:

    Bozo.jpg    1000 bytes (Tot: 1000 bytes)
    Clown.jpg   3090 bytes (Tot: 4090 bytes)
    Nuage.png   1500 bytes (Tot: 5590 bytes)
    <it stops here>

See also:
    @{" MaxCount " Link A_MAXCOUNT}
    @{" MaxTime  " Link A_MAXBYTES}

@EndNode

@Node A_NOBG "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/NoBG"

@{b}NoBG@{ub}  (NOBG/S)

If specified, no background image will be grabbed.  This is only useful in conjuntion with @{"Recurvise" Link A_RECURS}.

See also:
    @{" Recursive " Link A_RECURS}
    @{" NoHRef    " Link A_NOHREF}
    @{" NoSrc     " Link A_NOSRC}

@EndNode

@Node A_NOHREF "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/NoHRef"

@{b}NoHRef@{ub}  (NOHREF/S)

If specified, no file referenced will be grabbed.  This is only useful in conjuntion with @{"Recurvise" Link A_RECURS}.

An HREF file is a file on which you have to click to get it when you are in a web browser.  (Images, another web page, etc...)

See also:
    @{" Recursive " Link A_RECURS}
    @{" NoBG      " Link A_NOBG}
    @{" NoSrc     " Link A_NOSRC}

@EndNode

@Node A_NOSRC "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/NoSrc"

@{b}NoSrc@{ub}  (NOSRC/S)

If specified, all urls referred with a SRC tag will not be grabbed.  This is only useful in conjuntion with @{"Recursive" Link A_RECURS}.

SRC tags are used to specify an image to be shown with the text.  It is also used with non-standard kludges like the frames of NetScape.  Thus using NOSRC will prevent grabbing HTML referenced by frames AND images to be shown with the text.  I'm sorry but there is no way to distinguish them in this version.

See also:
    @{" Recursive " Link A_RECURS}
    @{" NoBG      " Link A_NOBG}
    @{" NoHRef    " Link A_NOHREF}

@EndNode

@Node A_PATTERN "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/Pattern"

@{b}Pattern@{ub}  (PATTERN=P/K) (Abbrev: P)

This allows you to specify an AmigaDOS pattern.  Each URL recursively found will only be added if it matchs this pattern.

@EndNode

@Node A_SAVEROOT "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/SaveRoot"

@{b}SaveRoot@{ub}  (SAVEROOT=SR/K) (Abbrev: SR)

This is the directory to use as a base for all files we receive.

Suppose we execute:

    GrabURL http://www.da.com/flowers/images/coquelicot.png sr ram:

Then the file will be saved as

    ram:www.da.com/flowers/images/coquelicot.png

The default root dir is set in GrabURL.  (See @{"Setting Defaults" Link DEFAULTS})

@EndNode

@Node A_WORKFILE "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/WorkFile"

@{b}WorkFile@{ub}  (WORKFILE=WF/K) (Abbrev: WF)

This is a file where all the urls processed are saved.  If the file exists at run-time, it will be loaded.  This way you can break a transfer and continue it later.

Each line of that file follow this template:

    <flag> <depth> <url>

See also:
    @{" Flags  " Link FLAGS}
    @{" Depth  " Link A_DEPTH}
    @{" InFile " Link A_INFILE}
    @{" URL    " Link A_URL}

@EndNode

@Node A_INFILE "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/InFile"

@{b}InFile@{ub} (INFILE=IN/K) (Abbrev: IN)

This is a file containing one url/line.  These urls are processed exactly as if they were given on the command line.

See also:
    @{" URL " Link A_URL}

@EndNode

@Node A_HELP "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/Help"

@{b}Help@{ub} (HELP/S) (Abbrev: H)

This gives the supported command line options and a brief description for each one.

@EndNode

@Node A_HEADONLY "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/HeaderOnly"

@{b}HeaderOnly@{ub}  (HEADERONLY=HO/S) (Abbrev: HO)

When present, this indicates GrabURL not to download the file but only the transfer header.

This is only useful in conjontion with @{"SaveHeaders" Link A_SAVEHEADS}.

@EndNode

@Node A_NODIRS "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/NoDirs"

@{b}NoDirs@{ub}  (NODIRS=ND/S) (Abbrev: ND)

This tells GrabURL not to create directory but to put the file in the current directory.  See @{"SaveRoot" Link A_SAVEROOT} for more explanations.

@EndNode

@Node A_NOTEXISTS "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/NotExists"

@{b}NotExists@{ub}  (NOTEXISTS=NE/S) (Abbrev: NE)

If given, GrabURL will only download files not already on disk.

@EndNode

@Node A_QUERY "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/Query"

@{b}Query@{ub}  (QUERY=Q/S) (Abbrev: Q)

If present, GrabURL will download files containing '?'.

Generally those files are used to send information to the server.  For example Search Engines use it, some counters use it, etc..

You should not use this switch.

@EndNode

@Node A_RECURS "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/Recursive"

@{b}Recursive@{ub}  (RECURSIVE=R/S) (Abbrev: R)

If present, GrabURL will scan each received HTML file for new urls.  These urls will then be added to the list and eventually to your disk.

See also:
    @{" Depth   " Link A_DEPTH}
    @{" Pattern " Link A_PATTERN}

@EndNode

@Node A_RETRY "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/Retry"

@{b}Retry@{ub}  (RETRY/S)

This tells GrabURL to retry to download files that failed the first time.

Each URLs marked Failed is only retried one time.  The retry happend after all the normal URLs have been processed.

@EndNode

@Node A_SAVEHEADS "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/SaveHeaders"

@{b}SaveHeaders@{ub} (SAVEHEADERS=SH/S) (Abbrev: SH)

If given GrabURL will save the transfer headers along with the files.
The header file has the same name than the file itself, with ".HDR" appended.

See also:
    @{" HeaderOnly " Link HEADONLY}

@EndNode

@Node A_DELAY "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/Delay"

@{b}Delay@{ub}  (DELAY/N)

This is the number of seconds to wait between each file.  You should not use a delay of 0 seconds if you plan to download a LOT of files - using this switch helps to diminish a little bit the load on the net.

The factory setting is 0 second and can be changed.  (See @{"Defaults" Link DEFAULTS})

@EndNode

@Node A_DEPTH "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/Depth"

@{b}Depth@{ub}  (DEPTH=D/K) (Abbrev: D)

This is the level of recursion to use.  (ie How deep to look in the files)

Level '0' means the "current" file.  All files contained in the current files have a level of "1" and so on.

Specifying 5 (along with the @{"Recursive" Link A_RECURS} switch) would  grab the  files  on the command line and specified with @{"InFile" Link A_INFILE}, giving them a "depth" of 5. The files contained in them would have a depth of 4.  Then 3, 2, 1 and finally 0.  The files contained in the depth-0 file won't be grabbed.

The default is "-1" which means "grab the world".

@EndNode

@Node A_MAXSIZE "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/MaxSize"

@{b}MaxSize@{ub}  (MAXSIZE=MS/N) (Abbrev: MS)

With this you can specify the maximal size a file can have in order to download it.

Ie "MaxSize 4096" will refuse a file having 4097 bytes but accepts 4096.

0 is the default which disable this option.

@EndNode

@Node A_MSL "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/MinSpaceLeft"

@{b}MinSpaceLeft@{ub}  (MINSPACELEFT=MSL/N) (Abbrev: MSL)

This is the minimal space to leave free on the device when downloading a file.  The default is 0 (disabled).

@EndNode

@Node A_IFMODIFIED "GrabURL.guide/Arguments/IfModified"

@{b}IfModified@{ub}  (IFMODIFIED=IM/S) (Abbrev: IM)

If present, each file that already exists on the disk will only be grabbed if the file on the server is newer than the one on the disk.

Some servers don't care about If-Modified information with .html files.  Others don't use this at all.  (It's worth a try!)

See also:
    @{"Defaults - Setting the timezone" Link DEFAULTS}

@EndNode

@Node DEFAULTS "GrabURL.guide/Defaults"

@{jcenter}@{b}@{u}Changing the defaults@{uu}@{ub}

@{jleft}The defaults are set directly in GrabURL.rexx using an ASCII editor.

When in the editor (ie GoldEd, CignusEd, ...), load "GrabURL.rexx" and go down some lines.  You should see a line beginning with:

    @{b}DoDefaults:@{ub}

You are now where the defaults are all set.

Here's a list of the defaults used for the command line @{"arguments" Link ARGUMENTS}:

@{b}opts.Url.Count@{ub}     (Factory: 0)@{lindent 4}
@{i}Must always be 0.@{ui}@{lindent 0}

@{b}opts.Depth@{ub}         (Factory: -1)@{lindent 4}
This is the default @{"depth" Link A_DEPTH} to use.  When doing recursion, this tells GrabURL not to care about depth.@{lindent 0}

@{b}opts.InFile@{ub}        (Factory: '')@{lindent 4}
This is the default file to load when starting GrabURL.  This file contains one url/line.  See @{"InFile" Link A_INFILE}.@{lindent 0}

@{b}opts.MaxSize@{ub}       (Factory: 0)@{lindent 4}
This is the maximal size a file can have in order to be grabbed.  See @{"MaxSize" Link A_MAXSIZE}.@{lindent 0}

@{b}opts.MinSpaceLeft@{ub}  (Factory: 0)@{lindent 4}
This is the minimal space to leave on disk when grabbing.  See @{"MinSpaceLeft" Link A_MSL}.@{lindent 0}

@{b}opts.Pattern@{ub}       (Factory: '')@{lindent 4}
This is the default pattern to use when doing recursion.  See @{"Pattern" Link A_PATTERN}.@{lindent 0}

@{b}opts.SaveRoot@{ub}      (Factory: 'Work:Urls/')@{lindent 4}
This is the default path where to save urls.  See @{"SaveRoot" Link A_SAVEROOT}.@{lindent 0}

@{b}opts.WorkFile@{ub}      (Factory: '')@{lindent 4}
This is the default @{"work file" Link A_WORKFILE} to use.@{lindent 0}

@{b}opts.Delay@{ub}         (Factory: 0)@{lindent 4}
This is how much seconds to wait between each grabbed file.  See @{"Delay" Link A_DELAY}.@{lindent 0}

@{b}opts.MaxTime@{ub}       (Factory: 0)@{lindent 4}
This is the maximal time in minutes to download.  See @{"MaxTime" Link A_MAXTIME}.@{lindent 0}

@{b}opts.MaxCount@{ub}      (Factory: 0)@{lindent 4}
This is the maximal number of file to download.  See @{"MaxCount" Link A_MAXCOUNT}.@{lindent 0}

@{b}opts.MaxBytes@{ub}      (Factory: 0)@{lindent 4}
This is the maximal number of bytes to download.  See @{"MaxBytes" Link A_MAXBYTES}.@{lindent 0}

Here's a list of the settings that cannot be modified on the command line:

@{b}def.KeepReceived@{ub}   (Factory: 1)@{lindent 4}
1 = Change the @{"flag" Link FLAGS} of received urls
0 = Remove them from the list@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.KeepFailed@{ub}     (Factory: 1)@{lindent 4}
1 = Change the @{"flag" Link FLAGS} of failed urls
0 = Remove urls that failed from the list.@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.KeepUnused@{ub}     (Factory: 1)@{lindent 4}
1 = Change the @{"flag" Link FLAGS} of urls that could not be processed.
0 = Remove them from the list.@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.FollowMoved@{ub}    (Factory: 1)@{lindent 4}
1 = Add the new URL given by the server when a "301 Moved" is received.
F = Mark it "Failed".
X = Mark "Error".@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.FollowTMoved@{ub}   (Factory: 1)@{lindent 4}
1 = Add the new URL given by the server when a "302 Moved Temporarily" is received.
F = Mark it "Failed".
X = Mark "Error".@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.Secure@{ub}         (Factory: 1)@{lindent 4}
1 = Save the workfile each time an url is modified (ie received, failed, removed, ...)
0 = Save the workfile only when GrabURL is completely done.@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.Accept@{ub}         (Factory: '*/*')@{lindent 4}
This is the @{"MIME" Link MIME} type(s) the remote host is allowed to send.@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.EMail@{ub}          (Factory: '')@{lindent 4}
This is the UserName/EMail address to send to each remote host we encounter.  Using '' forces GrabURL to send @{b}NO@{ub} user information across the net.  See @{"Browsing anonymously" Link ANONYMOUS}.  This information can look like:

    Serge Emond <emonds@jsp.umontreal.ca>@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.TimeZone@{ub}       (Factory: 300)@{lindent 4}
This is the number of minutes to @{i}add @{ui}to the local time to obtain GMT time.  It is only used when using the @{"IfModified" Link A_IFMODIFIED} argument.  The default is 5 hours (300 minutes) which is Québec/Ontario and the eastern part of USA.@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.WriteBufSize@{ub}   (Factory: 16*1024 (16k))@{lindent 4}
This is the size of the buffer @{"GrabHTTP" link "GrabHTTP.guide/main" 0} will use for the file itself.  The received data will be written only every def.WriteBufSize bytes.@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.Translate@{ub}      (Factory: '~:[]()'@{lindent 4}
If it is not '' then the characters given will be translated to chars in def.TranslateTo when saving the file to disk.  For example, if def.Translate="z!" and def.TranslateTo="_+" then all "z" in the filename will be changed to "_" and all "!" to "+".  To specify "*" you must write "**".  See @{"GrabHTTP" Link GrabHTTP.guide/main 0} documentation.@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.TranslateTo@{ub}    (Factory: copies("_", length(def.Translate)))@{lindent 4}
String to translate to.  See def.Translate.  This string MUST be at least the length of def.Translate.@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.TouchOldDirs@{ub}   (Factory: 1)@{lindent 4}
If 1, the already existing directory-names will have their date set to now.  (Ie http://hey.org/x/ creates "hey.org" then "hey.org/x".  If this option is 1 and some or all of these dirs exists, their date will be reset.)@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.TempFile@{ub}       (Factory: 't:GrabURL.'UID)@{lindent 4}
This is a temporary file used when scanning received HTML files to do @{"recursion" Link A_RECURSIVE}.  UID is a variable containing a unique ID and should be used in the name (as in the factory setting) to prevent collision if you run multiple GrabURL at the same time.@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.ParsePattern@{ub}   (Factory: '(FTP|HTTP)://#?')@{lindent 4}
Only urls matching this pattern are added to the url list.  If you want to see if there was ftp urls, allow them with this setting and use a workfile.  You can then see them by searching for "ftp:" in the workfile.@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.PasswordFile@{ub}   (Factory: '')@{lindent 4}
This is the filename of a data file containing password information.  See @{"Authentication" Link AUTHENTICATION} for more information.@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.Path@{ub}           (Factory: '')@{lindent 4}
This is the path where to find @{"ScanHTML" Link ScanHTML.guide/main 0}, @{"GrabHTTP" Link GrabHTTP.guide/main 0} & @{"UrlManager" Link UrlManager.guide/main 0} executables.@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.ScanHTML@{ub}      (Factory: def.Path'ScanHTML')@{lindent 4}
This is the path & name of @{"ScanHTML" Link ScanHTML.guide/main 0}.  See @{"Requirements" Link REQUIREMENTS}.@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.GrabHTTP@{ub}       (Factory: 'run <>nil: 'def.Path'')@{lindent 4}
This is the name of @{"GrabHTTP" Link GrabHTTP.guide/main 0}.  It must be started with "run".  See @{"Requirements" Link REQUIREMENTS}.@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.UrlManager@{ub}     (Factory: 'run <>nil: ''def.Path'UrlManager')@{lindent 4}
This is the name of @{"UrlManager" Link UrlManager.guide/main 0}.  It must be started with "run".  See @{"Requirements" Link REQUIREMENTS}.@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.Output@{ub}         (Factory: 'CONSOLE:')@{lindent 4}
This is the filename where GrabURL will output all its... output.  "CONSOLE:" will output to the console from which GrabURL was started.@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.Progress@{ub}       (Factory: 1)@{lindent 4}
If 1, tells @{"GrabHTTP" Link GrabHTTP.guide/main 0} to display progress informations in a window.  If 0, there's no window telling how much of the file has been received.@{lindent 0}

@{b}def.ExitOnClose@{ub}    (Factory: 0)@{lindent 4}
If 0, and the user presses the CloseGadget of @{"GrabHTTP" Link GrabHTTP.guide/main 0}'s window then the current file is marked Failed and the grab continues.  If 1, GrabURL exits.@{lindent 0}

@{b}um@{ub}                 (Factory: 'UM'UID)@{lindent 4}
This is the name of the port to use to communicate with @{"UrlManager" link "UrlManager.guide/main" 0}.  You should use the variable UID as in the factory setting to prevent collision.@{lindent 0}

@{b}gh@{ub}                 (Factory: 'GH'UID)@{lindent 4}
This is the name of the port to use to communicate with @{"GrabHTTP" link "GrabHTTP.guide/main" 0}.  You should use the variable UID as in the factory setting to prevent collision.@{lindent 0}

@EndNode

@Node MIME "GrabURL.guide/MIME Types"

@{jcenter}@{u}@{b}MIME@{ub}@{uu}

@{jleft}@{i}What follows come directly from AWeb's HTML documentation: @{ui}

MIME (Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions) is a mechanism for specifying and describing the format of Internet message bodies.  It was primarily designed for e-mail, but MIME types are used also to identify the type of data in the HTTP protocol, the most widely used protocol on the World Wide Web.

A MIME type consists of a @{i}type @{ui}and a @{i}subtype.@{ui}  The @{i}type @{ui}describes the major class of data, like text or image.  The @{i}subtype @{ui}is used for a subdivision of the major type into different formats, like GIF or JPEG images.

According to RFC 1521, the following official MIME types are defined:

@{b}TEXT/HTML@{ub}@{lindent 4}
This is a document in the HTML hypertext format.  Virtually all pages on the Web are in this format.@{lindent 0}

@{b}TEXT/PLAIN@{ub}@{lindent 4}
This type is used for plain text documents (normally in ASCII).@{lindent 0}

@{b}APPLICATION/OCTET-STREAM@{ub}@{lindent 4}
This describes a binary file.  The file could be processed by some application.  An example of this would be an LHA archive.@{lindent 0}

@{b}APPLICATION/POSTSCRIPT@{ub}@{lindent 4}
The document is in PostScript format.@{lindent 0}

@{b}IMAGE/GIF
IMAGE/JPEG@{ub}@{lindent 4}
These are images, in GIF and JPEG format.@{lindent 0}

@{b}AUDIO/BASIC@{ub}@{lindent 4}
This type is used for audio data encoded using 8-bit ISDN mu-law [PCM].@{lindent 0}

@{b}VIDEO/MPEG@{ub}@{lindent 4}
This is an animation in MPEG format.@{lindent 0}

In addition to these official types and subtypes, it is allowed to define extension MIME types and subtypes.  These should start with @{b}X-@{ub} to avoid collisions with future official MIME types.

@EndNode

@Node ANONYMOUS "GrabURL.guide/Browsing Anonymously"

@{jcenter}@{b}@{u}Browsing Anonymously@{uu}@{ub}
@{jleft}
An HTTP request can have a field containing email and name information about the user. This way, some people send their email address on every server they connect to. Most of the time it won't do anything but... there are twisted webmasters who use this information to send anoying emails ie to sell products.

It you want to see if your Web Browser sends such information without letting you knowing about it, have a look at this page: @{b}HTTP://www.uiuc.edu/~ejk/WWW-privacy.html@{ub}.

By default GrabURL won't send @{b}any@{ub} information about the user.  In fact, there is absolutely no function allowing to grab any information from your system without your consent so you can be sure it won't send anything.  :)

However you really should read about @{"Robot Guidelines" Link GrabHTTP.guide/GUIDELINES 0} in GrabHTTP.guide.

See the @{"Defaults" Link DEFAULTS 82} section to see how to set an EMail address with GrabURL.

@EndNode

